replies.commentBody:
@Independent,

Exactly right.  McAuliffe's claim that CRT was not being taught in schools was little more than a dodge to get around the real issue, and everyone knew it.

As for the 1619 Project: it should not be taught as fact, but of course neither should it be banned. Rather it should critiqued as a influential but also flawed piece of rhetoric.  So much potential learning that way!

@Independent   Why does Douthat always resort to the use of fancy language and “big” words when he is often saying what could be said simply?  Do you never stop to think about that?

The 1619 Project didn’t argue that the Revolution was fought “only” to maintain slavery, but the Boston Tea Party is the prime example that the Revolution was fought on the basis of economics.  Of the the nation’s founders half or more were slave holders and that is the modern and ironic equivalent of Manchin, a coal owning businessman, preventing environmental and social change legislation that would help his voters.   

But people who want to believe in the moral perfection of the US will always have a reason to vote for economic elites and for those who silently denigrate others who are different religiously, or are immigrants or are minority or are women.  The same sense of their own superiority in thinking pervades their very existence.  That includes Douthat.

@Independent 
Nikole Hannah-Jones may have stated that preservation of slavery was a primary motivator behind the Revolutionary War, but that single comment was not the primary focus of the 1619 project, at least as I experienced it.
Personally, I agree with the general premise that the institution of slavery has structurally influenced our country, and remains an so. However, it seems that the problem as it affects the VA election is that a lot white people take the mention of racism as a personal affront. Hannah Jones' take on the American revolution has more factual basis than do claims that Loudon Country school  children are being indoctrinated with CRT in school.

@Blue Moon 
"Democrats probably need a new way to talk about progressive ideology and education."

No.  Democrats need to abandon the progressive ideology and stay away from introducing progressive ideology in education.  They need start being a centrist party and forget the progressive ideology!

@Scott K 
"Americans are not going to be fooled any longer by new ways of talking about things."
How I wish this were true! But the people who turned out to vote in VA did so because they believed the lies about the C.R.T. being taught in public grade schools and the putative horrors of Beloved. I'd wager they didn't bother to do their "independent research" on either. They did it because they wanted to believe it. I abhor the party-speak now being promulgated at universities and the AMA (for God's sake!), I am irritated the virtu-signaling in capitalizing "Black" but not "White," including in this paper. But most of all I am frightened of the blindness and lack of judgment among both the Democrats and Republicans and the media, who are all blithely risking the destruction of our democracy. If we fall the rest of the world will follow, the puffed up egos of Elon Musk and Jeff Bezos notwithstanding.

@Steve What a deeply childish and privileged view.

So people didn't get EXACTLY what they wanted, and fast, so they allow back into power the people who have proven repeatedly that they don't want to help the citizenry with any of its problems? The Dems are punished for wanting to help people but fail to do it while the Repubs are rewarded for not wanting to do anything?

This country is doomed.

@Steve 

"Democrats in D.C. failed to deliver on any of the main campaign promises of 2020 or 2018 by Election Day 2021." 

Neither did Republicans. They didn't even try. So why did they win?

@Michael 

Most Republicans are not worried about what is true. They just repeat the talking points their leaders. That is why they all use exactly the same WORDS.

Many of these parents are not even parents.

@VMG I think you are incorrect (I think its about the lack of truck drivers)---but that's beside the point.

If the shortages persist - and we continue to fail to get enough truck drivers to unclog the ports and re-stock the shelves- then there WILL be comparisons to the old USSR in the run-up to the mid-terms: "this is what we will get if we allow the Bernie Socialists their way in creating a Democratic Socialist Paradise".

You can count on it.

@Angry Liberal  You write, "The too-late approval of vaccine for the kids means that some grandparents will not get to spend time during the Holidays with their grandchildren."

I do not have kids in the 5-11 age cohort, but it seems like on several occasions in the past few weeks, COVID vaccines have been "approved" for this age group.  But then a few days later, there's another approval, and then another, and then another.

When does the bureaucracy end and shots start going into kids' arms?  Can all of the people and committees that need to approve it all get in the same room at the same time and take care of all the approvals in the space of one day?  Do they have something better to do?

@Blueicap So... Joe Manchin, a Democrat in a 70% red-voting state, should become more progressive? You think a progressive Democrat would win in West Virginia. Be thnankful for Joe Manchin. He's the only reason Democrats have the Senate at this moment.

And if you think there's no difference between a Democratic Senate constrained by Joe Manchin and one run by Mitch McConnell...

Let me introduce you to Al Gore, the man who would have been President, but for progressives. Al Gore would have given us 20 years of action on climate change and would have kept us out of Iraq. The world would be vastly different and better today if he'd been President.

@Dan Take note of Al Gore. Back then progressives thought there was no difference between Gore and Bush. Look at the world today.

Same thing with regard to a Democratic Senate with Manchin holding a big key vs one run by Mich McConnell. 

Dems can do A LOT with the Senate, but progressives will have to settle for 1/2 to 1/3 of a loaf. Which is a whole lot better than nothing at all.

@Keith Kane Look at the mayoral election in Buffalo NY. A self-proclaimed “Democratic-socialist” India Walton, won the primary against a 4-term incumbent centrist Democrat, Byron Brown, who really didn’t bother to campaign. Yesterday, he appears to have won on a write-in campaign.

I listened to a long-form interview with Ms Walton, and I admire her tenacity and her commitment to the working poor; however, some of her policy ideas seemed utopian and naive at best, like reducing the police budget by $7.5 million — as crime is increasing nationwide. Not a winning hand.

Though it didn’t come from any Democratic lawmakers as far as I can see, the “defund the police” slogan has absolutely killed the down-ballot Dems in 2020 and continues in 2021. Add to that the GOP’s cynical manipulation of critical race theory — something not even taught in K-12 schools — and moderates ran away.

@Blueicap Honestly, the democratic infighting is probably no different from previous years. The difference is the ultra-slim majority requiring complete consensus. It would be difficult to achieve results no matter what. 

The real problem is Democrats don't know how to fight back when Republicans fight dirty with misinformation, outright false information, and dog whistles. 

Hate and rage and culture wars will always turn out voters more than anything rooted in actual policy. Trump is the only reason Democrats won anything in the last 5 years. Democrats need to play dirty or they will continue to lose against a party that will do literally anything (see: Jan 6 and post-Jan 6) to get and stay in power.

@Blueicap 

Nope, if Democrats had just passed the bi-partisan infrastructure bill, and stopped trying to push the BBB agenda they would have been MUCH better off.

Biden campaigned on being a moderate, he's trying to govern like a progressive

@McGloin 

Yet the centrist Democrat, Shontel Brown, won her congressional election in OH. She defeated a leftist, supported by Bernie Sanders, in the primary. 

So you might try to fit the VA election into some ruberic of "centrists Democrats lose, we need to nominate leftists" to make yourself feel better, but it's not clearly true.

@Tom So you don't want American history taught truthfully in schools.  

I'd rather have calculus that's made up and easy to do  where I can fill in my own answers than the hard stuff that takes hours of homework.   

That's not how it works, is it?

@Cary Broder   On the contrary, I think he does. That's exactly why he does not want (watered 
down) CRT. It has nothing to do with honest 
discussion about slavery, which should of course be welcomed in schools.

@Tom 

On the macro scale you don't need Schrodinger's equations at all to do physics. On the other hand, race potential plays a role in every part of society. 

In school Schrodinger is easily ignored, race not so much.

@She 

There's even a Marxist approach to calculus: 
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_manuscripts_of_Karl_Marx" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_manuscripts_of_Karl_Marx</a>

@Harry Finch 

Very true.

I make logical arguments all day and get no where.

@Had Enough 

For rejoinder to Robin DiAngelo's original sin theory inherent to her view, which worms inside people's religious psyche inculcating guilt, see Columbia Linguistics Professor's new book coming out addressing CRT and unwarranted assumptions capitalized in her book, "White Fragility." We should focus on understanding Other Americans different from ourselves, with different experiences, but through a lens of love rather than hate.

Poets like Terrence Hayes' "Assassin" derives its adrenaline from hate. Will not learn anything from listening except experience the feeling of being hated from one who suffered unjustly from hatred, or it will amplify the hatred already felt by a comparable reader. In contrast, rained out concert in Central Park featured Jon Baptiste's thrilling performance of "Freedom," which brought us together, in the rain. My Progressive era son met him, shook his hand, had brief but etched conversation outside Colbert's studio, after first memorable performance. Son also connected with Spike Lee at airport, who sat beside him in waiting area--Lee is a storyteller who tells the facts with heart that connects to audience of all races. We should build bridges between the races, acknowledging the facts on the ground but not widen the abyss by pushing the hate.

@Alexis 
This division you talk about does not happen in our homes,
only in public places. Let's think about that.

@Alexis 
Exactly. It is insanity to insist that we deny material reality at the expense of the safety of girls and women. Cervix havers, pregnant people, people seeking abortion. Males in female sport. Males in female prisons.

I cannot vote Republican, but I can in no way endorse a party who endorse the capitulation to religious fanaticism.

@JTinWestchester 

The Republican party is lousy with officeholders who have abandoned whatever principles they might have had to fulfill their ambitions by gaining power through Trump.  

But if I say this is a Faustian bargain, the newly elected Republicans might respond by banning Goethe and Verdi from any publicly-funded educational institution in Virginia.

@ML 
And there we go again, let’s just eliminate taxes altogether and see what happens. Because the spending goes on no matter which party is in power. Let’s see how roads and bridges fix themselves. 
Easy to propose and easy to dispose. It still comes back to fear as the playing card. Republicans win on fear, victimization and no taxes. Democrats play the fear card too but not as adept at galvanizing there apathetic base. The sun did come up this morning. Glass half full. Maybe time we all pause and look at what is ahead. Mother Nature could care less about our less than glorious selves.

@Gary 

Lower income people and households spend a greater proportion of their earnings on groceries so eliminated taxes on them disproportionately improves their lives.

Virginia is one of a small minority of states that taxes groceries.

@Arte Newman 
I was at a CRT town hall in Indiana Monday night - "Republicans will convince their voters that if they don't show up to the polls, liberals are going to indoctrinate their children with critical race theory and all will be lost. " 
is exactly what they said.  Along with branding it as Marxist ideology.

@Neildsmith 
If not for the intransigence and ignorance of the progressive newbies Nancy/Biden and Manchin would have the Build  Back Better programs passed by now. Watching your party get trounced is a sad way to be schooled on reality of how politics works in the real world. 
Now for the real problem moving forward. At some point no matter who is spending and both parties spend, we either tax or we fail. You can’t do both forever without ugly economic repercussions. Inequality has just become even more stark.

comments.commentBody:
For the Democratic party to retain my support, they must do the following:

Protect a woman's right to decide whether to continue with a pregnancy;

Protect our one home, planet Earth;

Acknowledge that racism does still exist, but dedicate any and all efforts to increase equal opportunities in the public schools, fortifying voting rights, and still be willing to talk about  the cultural issues that perpetuate poverty;

Strive for universal, public healthcare;

Support trans peoples right to live and work without discrimination, while acknowledging that women are a biological reality, that we are not an idea or testosterone level and are worthy of our privacy, dignity, and value, regardless if it hurts anyone's feelings.

If the party cannot do this, they will lose my support and vote.  

And - I am not alone.

replies.commentBody:
@Mike Quinlan 

Read John McWhorter for a nuanced view of those who opposed CRT. 

Obviously, not everyone who opposes CRT does so for the reasons John does, but I'd venture to guess many do.

@Lissa 

But children today, far too often, have very little interest in critical thinking, hence the numerous protest on college campuses against any ideas they haven't heard in their echo chambers.

I cannot recall the last time I saw a young person with a book in their hand; they're too busy looking at and taking photographs of themselves.

@Lissa 
“People aren’t even experts on their own children.”Hopefully Republican campaign consultants do not spend much time combing through comment sections in the NYT. If they do, this comment could find itself front and center in the next Republican campaign ad in,say, all of Virginia’s 2022 House races.
We reap what we sow.

@Ryan Biggs 

Messaging isn’t the problem.  Republican lies really aren’t the problem either.  The problem is that Democrats cannot cleave off identity politics and its many iterations, which are massively unpopular, from the Parties legislative agenda.  

The reason that so many working class Americans are voting against the Democratic Party even though the Party is attempting to pass legislation that will benefit those folks the most is because those people aren’t woke and don’t want to be.  They don’t support defunding the Police, they don’t want open borders, they don’t believe in cancel culture, they don’t believe in white privilege, etc.  Perhaps when these folks vote, they are voting AGAINST the radical social agenda of the Democratic Party.

@Brian The WHITE working-class has a high opioid addiction rate. The white working-class has a high suicide rate. The white working-class is opting out of college. The white working-class is struggling financially.

And yet, they vote for the party that "listens" to them but gives them ZERO assistance to solve their problems while giving the wealthy and corporations permanent tax cuts.

I think it's less about being "listened" to and more about the rejecting any views that move the country forward as a whole.

@francine lamb 

I would say that the sentiment behind this comment is true for both parties. Each has very vocal and loud political minorities that tend to overtake the main messaging. 

However, it is not wrong to be wary of these political minority voices because it only takes a minor shift to bring them into the mainstream. Take the 3.5 trillion deal that Biden has been pushing. That would have been laughed out of DC not 10 years ago.

@John And as a response, they are voting in authoritarianism.

Doesn't seem like a logical response.   Just throw democracy out the window because you aren't a fan of the cultural issues out there right now?
Wow.

@Dalton B. Miller As a physician I sure see a lot of folks who have put off healthcare until an emergency because they couldn't afford to see a doctor.  Couldn't afford their diabetes meds.  It's often quite late in the game by then.
Do the R's care?  No

Tax cuts for billionaires, yes.   R's are great at tax cuts. Not sure how that helps the poor though.

@Dalton B. Miller “ I said that under a minimum wage system the possibility of bargaining for the price of labor related to low or unskilled work has been removed from the equation.”

Right, and I am saying that the fact that most of minimum wage workers work under take-it-or-leave-it contract means that the possibility of bargaining for price of labor was close to non existent to begin with. In cases of big businesses like Walmart, the person offering the employee the contract won’t even have the authority to modify the contract on their own anyhow.

Also, your assumption that employers would compete with each other  to offer workers a better working condition doesn’t hold up that well when we are talking about low skilled workers. The employers just offer similar conditions, which tend to benefit them all precisely because they don’t have to compete with each other to give employees better conditions. Low skilled workers, unfortunately, tend to be more replaceable than others, and employers tend to care less about motivating them with better conditions.

@KT 

I don't agree with your general view of white people.  But, suppose you are correct.  Suppose further that right-thinking people - those in education, say, agree with you.  How would you expect that agreement to manifest itself in how they do their jobs?  Would you anticipate any political consequences to this?

On my side of the aisle, you appear to be making the second half of the "There's no such thing as CRT... and it's awesome!" argument.  The first comment I read here seems to capture the first half - paraphrasing: "my history-teaching daughter is being persecuted by the yahoos (in Massachusetts) merely for teaching a unit on African history."  I am skeptical.  I wish that commentator would provide some more background.  I'm guessing this unit dealt with colonialism in Africa; whether an American parent in 2021 would take that teaching personally depends a lot on how straight a line one is attempting to draw between then and now.

@MDM 

If that's true, that the left's policies are "wildly popular" than how did a more moderate Democrat beat a self-proclaimed socialist running as a Democrat win the Mayoral race in Buffalo as a write-in candidate?

Yes, a write-in candidate beat a socialist candidate in a left-leaning city. Do you realize how engaged the electorate has to be to know to write-in a candidate's name and not just fill in a bubble? It speaks to a high likelihood that far left politics are not popular, let alone wildly popular, in even Democrat polities.

@Mark @everydayispoetry

Would it help if we talked about "racial insensitivity" as distinct from "racism"? It seems that we did that more  often, ten years or so ago. Recently it's as if people have lost that ability.

The same individual can be guilty of both insensitivity and actual racism. But far more of us commit the former, and would be more open to critiques of our insensitivity. True racism should still be called out. But when everything is lumped together under "racism," that hinders problem solving.

@historian 

I learned about slavery and Jim Crow in sixth grade. In 1974. I survived without trauma. The complaints of these topics making children "uncomfortable" is ludicrous. 

There is no "both sides" consideration. Either slavery and Jim Crow were wrong, or they were not. It is taught that they were wrong because they were wrong.

@MG 
The answer is to keep teaching the truth. I would suggest that when you have a teacher parent meeting, maybe brining a text book would help. Ask them if you should just skip over the chapters about slavery and the suffering they endured. I would also suggest to not leave those thoughts in your head but bring them forward and lean in.

Pleas do not give up, my sister was a teacher and was punched in the mouth by a student in her first year but persevered. You too can bring these subjects up and persevere.

@MG there has to be a way to teach all these things without defining whiteness as an original sin. without describing one group of students as oppressors and others as oppressed.

I was learning about slavery in 6th grade, I remember being near traumatized by the graphic depictions of inhuman conditions, sickness, starvation and death captured peoples from Africa were subject to on the boats before they even reached our shores!

But I was never taught this toxic history of institutional powers in the US was a reflection on me. Now the message has changed. Some minority students are being told they will never succeed because the deck is stacked against them, and some white children are being taught they will always be racist. If democrats keep on this path we will become irrelevant, because the voters won't stand for it.

@historian 

Why is teaching the truth about our history a concern. What are these patents really “concerned”about?
 It certainly isn’t clear to me

@MG I am sorry, but that is not what CRT is about. It is not teaching about slavery. It is about blaming white people for the ills of todays black community.
I refuse to accept that premise. 
So do the majority of reasonable democrats and all Republicans.

@Jennie 
"attributing certain characteristics to racial/religious groups"

Do you mean like claiming that all White are inherently racist?

@MG

What is a bit ironic in your comment, is that you advocate teaching subjects that make the students « uncomfortable ». Yet, this is the same argument used by the so-called « progressive left » to ban the teaching of some literary works or to cancel speeches by certain public speakers that it views as offensive.

I am all for teaching « difficult » subjects that will challenge the students preconceptions and make them question their biases. But it has to be done by both sides, the right and the left.

@CF 
The initial thought seems to be that Youngkin won because of the CRT messaging. And I think the lie is appalling. But, it illustrates how social justice messaging turns off many white voters.

An alternative opinion: He won because Democratic in-fighting has made them incapable of fixing the current problems facing the Country. Or formulating a cohesive message. Americans want problems related to the broken supply chain and inflation fixed. Now. As Bill Clinton used to say, "Its the economy"

@Jennifer 

A win is a win. And considering Biden won the VA by 1 0points a year ago, I think you are missing the point. 

Just like the Democrats.

@Bonnie Huggins 

@Bonnie Huggins 

You're proving my point. No self-examination - just excoriating people you see as being too stupid to vote in their own interests. If national Democrats embraced your way of thinking, they'd be headed for exact outcome you claim to despise. 

You need to understand what people are frustrated about if you want to have a chance of winning them over. Douthat's column was important because too many progressives have dismissed the Republican CRT argument because "it isn't literally being taught in schools". Most people know that's a stretch, and understand that what was, not so long ago, viewed as a left-wing framework for analyzing how race affected the law is now taught to our kids as capital T Truth. Oppression/privilege are taught as realities rather than analytical frameworks. Many Democrats do not agree with this, and yet the strategy has been "let's ignore it and talk about how bad Trump/QAnon is" and just hope it will go away. Sound familiar? That's because it's ​exactly what the GOP does in its rhetoric re: Trump and the Democrats. 


My point is,  maybe try to understand what motivates the people who vote in a way you so abhor before substituting your own view of them (i.e. that they're irredeemable racists, corporatists, etc.). You might be surprised.

@John Marshall 

The inflation was driven by the massive stimulus put into the economy. Economists like Larry Summers and Des Lachman were warning about this in early 2021 but most Democratic politicians have fully bought into modern monetary theory. I'm not blaming Biden personally, but it's not unreasonable to blame Democratic policy writ large for what should have been a foreseeable issue.

As for the covid restrictions, I am vaccinated and mask up in indoor spaces. But what is the endgame? Why are only Republicans talking about an offramp for masking in schools? From my very liberal Twitter feed, it seems like many on the left are content to stay "vaxxed and masked" for the indefinite future and thus there's no sense of urgency to wind down restrictions. Even broaching this subject in many Democratic-leaning forums gets you eye rolls and shrugs, as if mandatory masking has no social costs on a population, especially for kids. A California study showed that vaccination rates, not the reinstitution of mask mandates, limited the impact of Delta.

@Bobby S. 

Except that CRT is not being taught in elementary schools or high schools It's taught at the college-level. People keep repeating this fact, yet it doesn't do any good because the people who choose to believe this are unreasonable, and it is impossible to reason with unreasonable people.

The unfortunate fact that so many people are gullible and stupid enough to willingly swallow a bald-face lie hook, line and sinker should disturb people. But after four years of Trump, it's not surprising.

@SMB Many of your points are valid; the use of the Southern strategy, the bizarre Pizzagate conspiracy, etc. But it is disingenuous to argue that CRT is not in schools. The Diversity, Equity and Inclusion training and administration popping up everywhere are the K-12 adaptation of CRT. And it is NOT about teaching accurate and complete history, there is an identity component that leaves little room for discussion.

Imagine sitting in "struggle sessions" with your colleagues where you must sit in a circle and confess what makes you feel uncomfortable about race, white-privilege, etc. By the way, all of these terms have been explicitly defined in a handbook that was created by a private company whose sole purpose is to create this content. If you try to have an open conversation or wish to keep your thoughts to yourself, you might be considered "non-compliant" and fragile. The methods used are to be pushed down through the ranks and into the classrooms. 

I am a public school educator.

@A Canadian View Progressive CRT proponents would like to limit play time of Ken Burnes’s work. They also believe that Ken Burns promoted Southern pride with his Civil War documentary, and therefore it must be replaced by something more anti-racist. Look into it. 

<a href="https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/why-we-need-new-civil-war-documentary-180971996" target="_blank">https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/why-we-need-new-civil-war-documentary-180971996</a>/

<a href="https://www.npr.org/2021/03/31/982706363/filmmakers-call-out-pbs-for-a-lack-of-diversity-over-reliance-on-ken-burns" target="_blank">https://www.npr.org/2021/03/31/982706363/filmmakers-call-out-pbs-for-a-lack-of-diversity-over-reliance-on-ken-burns</a>

@Frank L. Cocozzelli 

There's nothing ambiguous about compulsory diversity training, cancel culture, demands that men participate in women's sports and institutions which, like the Times, have swallowed the racial/gender grievance dogma whole.

The fact remains, Democrats may not run on it, and may not like it, but they're stuck with it.

@Stacie 

You do know that many countries kept their lower grade schools open most of the time for very important reasons ... without seeing hecatombs of dead children. 

The US had teachers' unions backed by the Democrats they fund so particularly children but also their parents suffered.

@Jack Sonville 
Virginians were never being taught CRT in their Public Schools. Youngkin's campaign just made this up.
But I agree with the rest of your post.

@1st generation immigrant 
Not teaching only the bad.  Unfortunately there is a movement growing in this country to whitewash historical truth, just as was done after the civil war.  We see it even playing out on a smaller scale with a Republican Party that wants to paint over and re-write what happened on Jan 6 as a tourist excursion, or these are the real patriots; that Ashli Babbit was a martyr.  
Youngkin promulgated a big lie that was cleverly designed to signal that he holds Trump’s racist values dear to his heart, while not sounding as vile as the dear leader himself.  And enough suburbanites bought it.

@Tony 

"CRT" is not being taught -- or even under consideration -- in public schools in Virginia or anywhere else. It's a bogeyman, a racist dog-whistle and god forbid we even consider teaching much less acknowledging any history but that of wealthy white men because we don't want anyone to feel anything but pride in our history!

The saddest part is that Republicans ran a campaign based on racism and won -- even by a narrow margin.

@Andrew 
And pass voting rights pronto.  That means getting Manchin to actually become part of the Democratic Party and not just use the brand to further his own ambitions.  

Or use infrastructure as leverage.  Play noice Joe and you’ll get some nice projects for WVA.  Keep up this obstruction and you’ll get NADA.

@Justin 
I have come to the conclusion that Pres. Biden is vey naive about Sen. Manchin.  Even yesterday he was saying that Manchin will support the bill.  Manchin wants Zero investment in social capital because that means that his family’s wealth form coal and pharmaceutical interests will be taxed higher.  Manchin will never support the bills.  Even if he does, he will only do so by the time it is too late to make a difference to the ‘22 elections.
Biden needs to summon his inner LBJ and tell Manchin that he either supports the BBB bill or Zero dollars from infrastructure will be spent in WVA.

@Larry 
Don’t count on not hearing Republican bleating about voter fraud, even in VA. 

Republicans know the big games are in ‘22 and ‘24 and will do everything they can to keep that fire burning in case the midterms and presidential elections are close in the D favor.

@Alcidious 
Manchin and Sinema have been the ones grandstanding.  Progressives have compromised down from $6T, to $3.5T and now to $1.75 T and still Manchin is not comfortable and is now holding out the prospect of a deal by Thanksgiving.  He had confided to confidantes that he prefers ZERO and that is what he is aiming for. 

Rep Jayapal has been nothing but conciliatory in this process, defending this as the President’s agenda and adjusting downward when Biden has signaled the need to do so.  Manchin just keeps moving the goal posts for whatever reasons. Last objection was taxes.  Before that it was the clean energy provisions.   He just doesn’t want his family to pay higher taxes on capital gains from his coal interests.

@David Lindsay Jr. 
if they passed the infrastructure bill Manchin and Sinema would simply walk away from the president’s agenda / Build back better.  Biden and the progressives would have lost all leverage.
But it should be obvious by now that Manchin and probably Sinema will never vote for the president’s agenda anyway.  The progressives have made big concessions throughout this process $6T to $3.5 T to $1.75T and still Manchin and Sinema tease and move the goal posts. Manchin is now posturing that a deal could be had by Thanksgiving.  He is just running out the clock.  Anyone who thinks he has any integrity is deluding themselves.

@M. Callahan 

Biden was picked out of a couple dozen. This goes back to the theory Bernie could of beat Trump. 

The Democrats moved to the left in Texas didn't they? Is the country really that much different.

@Renee M

I hope the Democrats take your theories to heart and run on it. But then I’m a Republican. 
Good fortunes.

@NovaParent The "fundamentals of mathematics" is not in fact vague. Look it up. It cites specific math concepts. And a quick wikipedia search also shows that "academic preparedness" in Govner's schools comes down to testing and expensive text prep for which there was no public option. That is hardly about merit, now is it?

A lot of comfortable parents consider their kids achievements to be pure merit when in fact it has a lot to do with their socio-economic background. 

So yeah, I'm sure Virginia parents wanted to keep their privileges.

@Bruce Rozenblit 
The hard progressive ideas were never going to fly despite AOC and her gang. Too much of the country is not for that even if their individual districts are. They need to focus on getting things done like the infrastructure bill alone, not with the other stuff attached, even though they may be worthy ideas. Try to prove you can do something except disagree, because the right doesn’t disagree, they agree. Accomplish what you can, use that to build support, then maybe you can win more elections. 

Politicians look at the next election, statesmen look at the next generation.

@Independent 

Progressive leaders on TV this morning are blaming the debacle on not having a candidate that excites the base and messaging. 

They refuse to acknowledge America does not want what they're selling. They are a brick wall that will cost us the House and the Senate next year.

@Kip Leitner 

Progressives lost every election for mayor last night to moderate democrats including in Buffalo, Boston, New York, Seattle and a defund the police ballot initiative in Minneapolis. Democrats lost VA and will likely squeak out the tiniest margin of victory in deep blue NJ.

Progressives are the blind that will not see.

@Bruce Rozenblit 

Many of those commenting seem to feel all we need to do is get the Republicans to promise not to run nasty, deceptive campaigns that infuse race and cultural themes into the mix and Progressive ideas will triumph.

